(cg:chk-my-solution \"~/quicklisp/local-projects/5ig/Example/pt/q1.lisp\")
#+END_SRC

Write a Common Lisp function called DOT-PRODUCT-LIST that takes two lists of numbers of equal length. The function should return a list where each element is the product of the numbers at that position. 

In your implementation, you must write and use a helper function called MULTIPLY-RECORDS that takes two numbers and returns their product. You may implement this as a standalone function or locally using LABELS.

#+BEGIN_SRC lisp
The expression below

  (DOT-PRODUCT-LIST '(1 2 3) '(4 5 6))

should evaluate to

  (4 10 18)
#+END_SRC

#+BEGIN_SRC lisp
The expression below

  (DOT-PRODUCT-LIST NIL NIL)

should evaluate to

  NIL
#+END_SRC
")
  (:HIDDEN
   (PROGN
    (DECLAIM (NOTINLINE TESTER::DOT-PRODUCT-LIST))
    (TESTER::TEST TESTER::Q1-DOT-PRODUCT-LIST-HIDDEN-TEST
        (TESTER::PATH)
      (TESTER::IS
       (EQUALP (TESTER::DOT-PRODUCT-LIST '(10 20) '(0.5 2)) '(5.0 40))
       TESTER::PATH)
      (TESTER::IS (EQUALP (TESTER::DOT-PRODUCT-LIST '(-1 -2) '(3 4)) '(-3 -8))
                  TESTER::PATH)
      (TESTER::IS (EQUALP (TESTER::DOT-PRODUCT-LIST '(100) '(100)) '(10000))
                  TESTER::PATH))))
  (:GIVEN
   (PROGN
    (DECLAIM (NOTINLINE TESTER::DOT-PRODUCT-LIST))
    (TESTER::TEST TESTER::Q1-DOT-PRODUCT-LIST-GIVEN-TEST
        (TESTER::PATH)
      (TESTER::IS
       (EQUALP (TESTER::DOT-PRODUCT-LIST '(1 2 3) '(4 5 6)) '(4 10 18))
       TESTER::PATH)
      (TESTER::IS (EQUALP (TESTER::DOT-PRODUCT-LIST NIL NIL) NIL)
                  TESTER::PATH))))
  (:ASKED-FUNCTION TESTER::DOT-PRODUCT-LIST))
